1
00:01:40,640 --> 00:01:43,632
How I got into this predicament,
I'll never know.

2
00:01:43,760 --> 00:01:45,716
Absolutely incredible.

3
00:01:45,840 --> 00:01:49,116
To be executed for a crime
I never committed.

4
00:01:49,240 --> 00:01:51,879
Of course,
isn't all mankind in the same boat?

5
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:55,629
Isn't all mankind ultimately executed
for a crime it never committed?

6
00:01:56,080 --> 00:01:58,594
The difference is
that all men go eventually,

7
00:01:58,720 --> 00:02:00,915
but I go six o'clock tomorrow morning.

8
00:02:01,040 --> 00:02:05,397
I was supposed to go at fýve o'clock,
but I have a smart lawyer. Got leniency.

9
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:08,434
I've a tremendous yearning
to be young again.

10
00:02:08,880 --> 00:02:13,112
A boy. Such happy memories
at our summer house.

11
00:02:13,240 --> 00:02:16,038
Uncle Nikolai with his wonderful laugh.

12
00:02:24,280 --> 00:02:26,157
God, he was repulsive.

13
00:02:26,280 --> 00:02:29,590
There was Grandpa and Grandma,
who had been married for 50 years

14
00:02:29,720 --> 00:02:33,315
and still felt as deeply about one another
as the day they met.

15
00:02:34,960 --> 00:02:38,191
And my own father,
a handsome and generous man.

16
00:02:38,320 --> 00:02:42,677
In addition to our summer and winter
estate, he owned a valuable piece of land.

17
00:02:42,800 --> 00:02:47,635
True, it was a small piece. But he carried
it with him wherever he went.

18
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:51,515
Dimitri Pietrovich!
I would like to buy your land.

19
00:02:51,640 --> 00:02:54,438
This land is not for sale.

20
00:02:54,560 --> 00:02:58,189
Some day, I hope to build on it.

21
00:02:58,320 --> 00:03:00,834
He was an idiot. But I loved him.

22
00:03:00,960 --> 00:03:05,476
Then there was mother, who made
the most delicious blintzes in the world.

23
00:03:07,920 --> 00:03:10,992
Of course, there was Old Gregor,
and his son, Young Gregor.

24
00:03:11,120 --> 00:03:13,793
Young Gregor's son
was older than Old Gregor.

25
00:03:13,920 --> 00:03:16,798
Nobody could fýgure out
how that happened.

26
00:03:16,920 --> 00:03:20,629
My two brothers, lvan and Mikhail,
used to play amusing little games.

27
00:03:20,760 --> 00:03:24,070
But I had a completely different
concept of myself as a child.

28
00:03:26,760 --> 00:03:31,390
My fýrst experience with death
was with one of our serfs, Old Nehamkin.

29
00:03:32,040 --> 00:03:36,556
Old Nehamkin was on the roof, putting up
a lightning rod, when a storm broke out.

30
00:03:37,320 --> 00:03:40,551
After he failed to show up for dinner,
Mother went to look for him.

31
00:03:40,680 --> 00:03:44,195
What is it, Old Nehamkin?
You're not looking well.

32
00:03:44,320 --> 00:03:47,198
Are you OK? You feel all right?

33
00:03:47,600 --> 00:03:49,636
We laid Old Nehamkin to rest,

34
00:03:49,760 --> 00:03:52,433
and that night
I had a strange and vivid dream.

35
00:04:15,600 --> 00:04:20,151
I knew that after that dream I would
not grow up to be an ordinary man.

36
00:04:20,280 --> 00:04:22,350
I spoke often with Father Nikolai,

37
00:04:22,480 --> 00:04:25,199
who was always dressed in black
with a black beard.

38
00:04:25,320 --> 00:04:27,675
For years
I thought he was an Italian widow.

39
00:04:27,800 --> 00:04:31,873
Every action has a cause. The universe
exists, therefore it has a cause.

40
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:35,151
It follows God created the universe,
therefore He exists.

41
00:04:35,280 --> 00:04:38,078
And yet Spinoza didn't believe
in the Holy Trinity.

42
00:04:38,200 --> 00:04:40,236
- Spinoza was a Jew.
- What's a Jew?

43
00:04:40,360 --> 00:04:44,148
You never saw a Jew?
Here. I have some sketches.

44
00:04:45,720 --> 00:04:49,269
- There are Jews.
- No kidding.

45
00:04:49,400 --> 00:04:53,075
- They all have these horns?
- No, this is the Russian Jew.

46
00:04:53,200 --> 00:04:55,668
The German Jew has these stripes.

47
00:04:55,800 --> 00:04:58,234
I recall my fýrst mystical vision.

48
00:04:58,360 --> 00:05:00,749
I was in the woods, thinking about Christ.

49
00:05:00,880 --> 00:05:04,429
If He was a carpenter, I wondered
what He'd charge for book shelves?

50
00:05:04,560 --> 00:05:05,959
Suddenly...

51
00:05:06,800 --> 00:05:08,916
- Who are you?
- Death.

52
00:05:09,480 --> 00:05:11,471
What happens after we die?

53
00:05:11,600 --> 00:05:14,160
Is there a hell? Is there a God?

54
00:05:15,240 --> 00:05:17,356
Do we live again?

55
00:05:17,480 --> 00:05:20,916
All right. Let me ask one key question.

56
00:05:21,920 --> 00:05:25,833
- Are there girls?
- You're an interesting young man.

57
00:05:25,960 --> 00:05:27,757
We'll meet again.

58
00:05:27,880 --> 00:05:30,474
- Don't bother.
- It's no bother.

59
00:05:32,160 --> 00:05:35,118
I grew to full manhood.
Actually, fýve foot six,

60
00:05:35,240 --> 00:05:39,279
which is technically not full manhood
in Russia, but you can own property.

61
00:05:39,440 --> 00:05:43,672
Over 5'3", you can own land. Under 5'3",
you need permission from the Tsar.

62
00:06:06,520 --> 00:06:08,590
We were three healthy men.

63
00:06:08,720 --> 00:06:10,676
My brother lvan.

64
00:06:13,040 --> 00:06:14,996
My brother Mikhail.

65
00:06:16,840 --> 00:06:18,796
And myself.

66
00:06:23,640 --> 00:06:25,915
Finally, there was my cousin Sonja.

67
00:06:26,040 --> 00:06:29,430
In addition to being the most beautiful
woman I had ever seen,

68
00:06:29,560 --> 00:06:33,758
she was one of the few people
I could have deep conversations with.

69
00:06:34,680 --> 00:06:38,275
Boris, look at this leaf. Isn't it perfect?

70
00:06:38,800 --> 00:06:40,950
And this one? Look.

71
00:06:41,080 --> 00:06:45,596
Oh, yeah. I definitely think that
this is the best of all possible worlds.

72
00:06:45,720 --> 00:06:49,349
- It's certainly the most expensive.
- Isn't nature incredible?

73
00:06:50,520 --> 00:06:54,115
To me, nature is... I dunno,
spiders and bugs and,

74
00:06:54,240 --> 00:06:56,196
big fish eating little fish.

75
00:06:56,320 --> 00:06:59,790
And plants eating plants
and animals eating...

76
00:06:59,920 --> 00:07:01,876
It's like an enormous restaurant.

77
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:04,958
Yes, but if God created it,
it has to be beautiful,

78
00:07:05,080 --> 00:07:07,753
even if His plan's not apparent
to us at the moment.

79
00:07:07,880 --> 00:07:10,189
Sonja, what if there is no God?

80
00:07:10,320 --> 00:07:12,675
Boris Dimitrovitch, are you joking?

81
00:07:12,800 --> 00:07:15,314
What if we're just
a bunch of absurd people

82
00:07:15,440 --> 00:07:18,079
who are running around
with no rhyme or reason?

83
00:07:18,200 --> 00:07:20,839
But if there is no God,
then life has no meaning.

84
00:07:20,960 --> 00:07:23,838
Why go on living?
Why not just commit suicide?

85
00:07:23,960 --> 00:07:26,679
Well, let's not get hysterical.
I could be wrong.

86
00:07:26,800 --> 00:07:29,837
I'd hate to blow my brains out,
then see they found something.

87
00:07:29,960 --> 00:07:33,111
Boris. Let me show you
how absurd your position is.

88
00:07:33,640 --> 00:07:38,031
Let's say there is no God, and each man
is free to do exactly as he chooses.

89
00:07:38,160 --> 00:07:40,720
What prevents you
from murdering somebody?

90
00:07:40,840 --> 00:07:44,116
- Murder's immoral.
- Immorality is subjective.

91
00:07:44,240 --> 00:07:46,356
Yes, but subjectivity is objective.

92
00:07:46,880 --> 00:07:48,916
Not in a rational scheme of perception.

93
00:07:49,040 --> 00:07:51,429
Perception is irrational.
It implies imminence.

94
00:07:51,560 --> 00:07:55,314
But judgment of any system
of phenomena exists

95
00:07:55,440 --> 00:07:58,989
in any rational, metaphysical or
epistemological contradiction

96
00:07:59,120 --> 00:08:03,591
to an abstracted empirical concept
such as being, or to be, or to occur

97
00:08:03,720 --> 00:08:06,075
in the thing itself, or of the thing itself.

98
00:08:06,200 --> 00:08:08,111
Yeah, I've said that many times.

99
00:08:08,240 --> 00:08:11,676
Boris, we must believe in God.

100
00:08:12,200 --> 00:08:16,034
If I could just see a miracle,
just one miracle.

101
00:08:16,160 --> 00:08:20,597
If I could see a burning bush,
or the seas part, or...

102
00:08:20,720 --> 00:08:23,393
Or my Uncle Sasha pick up a check.

103
00:08:24,920 --> 00:08:27,832
We should go back downstairs.

104
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:30,719
By now
the last golden streaks of the sunset

105
00:08:30,840 --> 00:08:33,673
are vanishing behind the western hills.

106
00:08:33,800 --> 00:08:37,952
Soon the dark blanket of night
shall settle over us all.

107
00:08:38,080 --> 00:08:41,470
Hey, you've been going
to finishing school.

108
00:08:42,680 --> 00:08:46,719
Hey, are you dating any Russians
I should know about?

109
00:08:47,720 --> 00:08:49,790
Well, Minskov has proposed.

110
00:08:49,920 --> 00:08:51,876
And he's very sweet and wealthy.

111
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:55,117
But the age difference is too great.
I'm 28 and he's 81.

112
00:08:55,240 --> 00:08:59,518
- Oh, that is big.
- When I'm 50, he'll be 103.

113
00:08:59,640 --> 00:09:01,596
That's a bad age for a man. They slow up.

114
00:09:01,720 --> 00:09:04,075
And Voskovec
has made his intentions clear.

115
00:09:04,200 --> 00:09:06,873
But he deals in herring,
and he always smells of it.

116
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:09,355
He even bought me
herring-scented cologne.

117
00:09:09,480 --> 00:09:11,948
That's probably
why the cat follows you around.

118
00:09:12,080 --> 00:09:13,991
Love is everything, Boris.

119
00:09:14,120 --> 00:09:17,351
I wanna meet some man
and scale the heights of passion.

120
00:09:17,480 --> 00:09:21,029
Some man who embodies
the three great aspects of love.

121
00:09:21,160 --> 00:09:24,755
Intellectual, spiritual and sensual.

122
00:09:24,880 --> 00:09:28,839
Well, there's not too many of us
around, but it can be done.

123
00:09:29,480 --> 00:09:32,756
- So many women settle cheaply.
- I know. Poor things.

124
00:09:32,880 --> 00:09:35,997
- They marry for money.
- Money! Well, money.

125
00:09:36,120 --> 00:09:38,793
But I feel as though
my life would be wasted

126
00:09:38,920 --> 00:09:42,356
if I didn't love deeply
with a man whose mind I respected,

127
00:09:42,480 --> 00:09:44,596
whose spirituality equalled mine,

128
00:09:44,720 --> 00:09:47,439
and who had the same lustful appetite

129
00:09:47,560 --> 00:09:50,393
for sensual passion that drives me insane.

130
00:09:50,920 --> 00:09:53,229
You're an incredibly complex woman.

131
00:09:53,720 --> 00:09:57,429
I guess you could say
I'm half saint, half whore.

132
00:09:57,880 --> 00:09:59,916
Here's hoping I get the half that eats.

133
00:10:00,040 --> 00:10:01,837
- Boris.
- Yes?

134
00:10:01,960 --> 00:10:04,110
I have a confession to make.

135
00:10:04,480 --> 00:10:07,756
Ever since you and I were little children,

136
00:10:07,880 --> 00:10:10,189
I've been in love with your brother lvan.

137
00:10:10,320 --> 00:10:12,038
It's only nat...

138
00:10:12,160 --> 00:10:16,551
Ivan? You're kidding! He can barely write
his name in the ground with a stick.

139
00:10:16,680 --> 00:10:18,511
He has true animal magnetism.

140
00:10:18,640 --> 00:10:22,076
All that talk about some perfect love
and you're hot for lvan?

141
00:10:22,200 --> 00:10:24,395
- He kissed me.
- Any place I should know?

142
00:10:24,520 --> 00:10:28,433
- It warmed the cockles of my heart.
- Great. Nothing like hot cockles.

143
00:10:28,560 --> 00:10:30,516
I think he's going to propose to me.

144
00:10:30,640 --> 00:10:34,030
But he's a gambler and a drinker,
with a Neanderthal mentality.

145
00:10:34,160 --> 00:10:37,357
I mean, I love him like a brother.
Just not one of mine.

146
00:10:37,480 --> 00:10:40,358
Do you hear that commotion?
What's going on downstairs?

147
00:10:41,040 --> 00:10:43,918
Have you heard the news?
Napoleon has invaded Austria.

148
00:10:44,040 --> 00:10:47,999
- Why? Is he out of Courvoisier?
- A chance to taste the glories of battle.

149
00:10:48,120 --> 00:10:49,951
Check with me when it's over...

150
00:10:50,080 --> 00:10:54,278
- No, Boris. You're going to fight.
- You're gonna have your head examined.

151
00:10:54,400 --> 00:10:57,597
- We leave the day after tomorrow.
- Fellas, I'm a pacifist.

152
00:10:57,720 --> 00:11:01,508
- I don't believe in war.
- He doesn't believe in war.

153
00:11:01,640 --> 00:11:03,870
Napoleon, he believes in war.

154
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:07,595
What are you going to do when
the French soldiers rape your sister?

155
00:11:07,720 --> 00:11:09,756
- I don't have one.
- That's no answer.

156
00:11:09,880 --> 00:11:14,192
- They won't rape lvan. They'd throw up.
- Don't disgrace me in front of my friends.

157
00:11:14,320 --> 00:11:18,279
What good is war? We kill Frenchmen,
they kill Russians, then it's Easter.

158
00:11:18,400 --> 00:11:20,868
Boris, you're talking about Mother Russia.

159
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:25,437
She's not my mother. My mother wouldn't
let her youngest get shrapnel in his gums.

160
00:11:25,560 --> 00:11:29,439
- Get away from me.
- I can't believe what I'm seeing.

161
00:11:29,560 --> 00:11:33,519
- He has a yellow streak down his back.
- No, it runs across.

162
00:11:33,640 --> 00:11:36,393
- Boris, you're a coward.
- Yes, but a militant coward.

163
00:11:36,520 --> 00:11:39,876
Boris. Medals... We'll get medals.

164
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:42,992
Take it easy, lvan.
You've got to cut down on your raw meat.

165
00:11:43,160 --> 00:11:45,515
He'll go and he'll fight.

166
00:11:45,640 --> 00:11:48,950
And I hope they will put him
in the front lines.

167
00:11:49,080 --> 00:11:51,514
Thanks a lot, Mum. My mother, folks.

168
00:11:53,080 --> 00:11:56,709
This is crazy. I can't shoot a gun.
I was meant to write poetry.

169
00:11:56,840 --> 00:12:00,435
Sonja, I'm not the army type.
I slept with the light on till I was 30.

170
00:12:00,560 --> 00:12:02,437
I can't shower with other men.

171
00:12:02,560 --> 00:12:05,028
Friends. My friends.

172
00:12:06,240 --> 00:12:10,438
On the eve of this glorious occasion,
I have an announcement to make.

173
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:16,836
Because we go into battle, perhaps
never to see our loved ones again,

174
00:12:16,960 --> 00:12:20,430
I wish to announce
that tomorrow I intend to marry.

175
00:12:21,960 --> 00:12:26,078
I'm going to take as my bride
a woman I have grown up with.

176
00:12:27,360 --> 00:12:29,112
Anna lvanova.

177
00:12:30,920 --> 00:12:32,876
Ivan.

178
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:36,549
I'm sorry. I should have told you.

179
00:12:38,640 --> 00:12:41,108
I also have an announcement to make.

180
00:12:41,240 --> 00:12:43,879
Tomorrow, I too get married.

181
00:12:44,600 --> 00:12:47,398
I have been proposed to
and have accepted the hand of

182
00:12:47,520 --> 00:12:51,069
Sergei lvanovich Minskov.

183
00:12:57,760 --> 00:13:02,515
Yes... I mean Leonid Voskovec,
the herring merchant.

184
00:14:10,960 --> 00:14:12,916
You! Get out here!

185
00:14:21,680 --> 00:14:24,752
You're the worst soldier I ever seen.

186
00:14:25,440 --> 00:14:28,273
- You ignorammus!
- Ignoramus, sir.

187
00:14:28,400 --> 00:14:31,676
- You want a dishonourable discharge?
- Yes, sir. Or a furlough.

188
00:14:31,800 --> 00:14:34,360
Goddamn you!
You love Russia, don't you?

189
00:14:34,480 --> 00:14:36,357
- Yessir.
- Louder!

190
00:14:36,480 --> 00:14:38,232
- You like it here?
- Yessir!

191
00:14:38,360 --> 00:14:42,353
- You want to make a career in the army?
- Well, let's not get carried away.

192
00:14:42,480 --> 00:14:44,710
You can clean the mess hall
and the latrine!

193
00:14:44,840 --> 00:14:46,796
Yessir. How will I tell the difference?

194
00:14:46,920 --> 00:14:47,989
OK.

195
00:14:48,120 --> 00:14:51,032
One, two! One, two! One, two!

196
00:14:51,160 --> 00:14:53,913
Three is next, if you're having any trouble.

197
00:15:41,440 --> 00:15:44,876
Naturally, the war affects
the herring industry.

198
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:46,956
The ports are blockaded.

199
00:15:47,080 --> 00:15:50,834
Fresh shipments of the herring
become more difficult to obtain.

200
00:15:50,960 --> 00:15:54,589
And, of course, when something
hurts herring, it hurts me.

201
00:15:56,160 --> 00:15:58,116
What people don't understand

202
00:15:58,240 --> 00:16:00,879
is that there are hundreds
of types of herring,

203
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:03,753
each with its own interesting history.

204
00:16:04,960 --> 00:16:07,155
Sonja. Are you OK?

205
00:16:10,080 --> 00:16:11,957
Oh, yes.

206
00:16:12,080 --> 00:16:13,593
But I've talked long enough.

207
00:16:13,720 --> 00:16:18,430
Why don't you two play, as I have got
some important business to attend to?

208
00:16:18,920 --> 00:16:21,036
A capital idea.

209
00:16:23,040 --> 00:16:25,429
Ready? And a one and a two...

210
00:16:25,560 --> 00:16:27,278
And...

211
00:16:42,120 --> 00:16:44,190
- You stopped.
- What would you think

212
00:16:44,320 --> 00:16:49,678
if I told you you were one of the most
beautiful women I have ever seen?

213
00:16:50,400 --> 00:16:54,632
I'd think what a mad fool he is.

214
00:16:54,760 --> 00:16:58,912
And what would you say
if I suddenly put my arms around you?

215
00:16:59,040 --> 00:17:02,555
I'd think what a mad,
impetuous fool he is.

216
00:17:03,120 --> 00:17:05,918
And what would you think if I kissed you?

217
00:17:06,040 --> 00:17:09,919
I'd think what a mad,
impetuous, wonderful fool he is.

218
00:17:11,200 --> 00:17:12,838
- Don't!
- I must!

219
00:17:12,960 --> 00:17:16,111
- We just ate.
- Your skin, it is so beautiful.

220
00:17:16,240 --> 00:17:18,356
Yes, I know. It covers my whole body.

221
00:17:18,480 --> 00:17:20,311
I must have you.

222
00:17:20,440 --> 00:17:23,273
No, not on the piano. It's a rented piano.

223
00:17:23,400 --> 00:17:25,960
Darling, my darling, my...

224
00:17:26,600 --> 00:17:28,113
Sonja!

225
00:17:28,640 --> 00:17:31,359
Sonja, did you see a jar of wine sauce?

226
00:17:35,120 --> 00:17:37,759
- Come to my quarters tomorrow at three.
- I can't.

227
00:17:37,880 --> 00:17:40,314
- Please!
- It's immoral. What time?

228
00:17:40,440 --> 00:17:44,069
- Who is to say what is moral?
- Morality is subjective.

229
00:17:44,200 --> 00:17:46,430
Subjectivity is objective.

230
00:17:46,560 --> 00:17:49,233
Moral notions imply attributes
to substances

231
00:17:49,360 --> 00:17:51,555
which exist only in relational duality.

232
00:17:51,680 --> 00:17:55,514
Not as an essential extension
of ontological existence.

233
00:17:55,640 --> 00:17:58,029
Can we not talk about sex so much?

234
00:17:58,160 --> 00:18:01,197
- I'm terribly sorry.
- You'd better go.

